From Stan Friesen Subject Re MAJOR VIEWS OF THE TRINITY In article M you write I fear orthodox theologians have been overly in love with paradox to the extent that well meaning people think they've just flat out There's no problem with things being both and if the are different parts of the But they're in some way different aspects modes or whatever of one If you accept economic trinitarianism it's possible that you don't have any substantive difference with the standard Is it possible that you just don't find the neo Platonic explanation illuminating clh I would put it stronger than I consider it Simply put I do not see any way that a Platonic essence could have any real Essence in the Platonic sense does not have any referent as far as I can tell it is just an imaginary concept invented to provide an explanation for things better explained in other So to attribute an 'essence' to God is to attribute to him something that does not exist Thus the orthodox Platonic formulation seems to leave the unity of God in limbo since it is based on a non existant 'essence' thus failing to avoid the very problem it was supposed to Thus to me the unity of God must be primary and the triality must be secondary must be modal or aspectual relating to roles or to modes of interaction since otherwise there is no meaning to saying God is formerly tdatirv sarima or I think one can read Augustine as saying something consistent with your His De Trinitate which has been very influential in the West defines the distinction among the persons You're probably at one extreme of orthodox views but I'm not sure your views are necessary incompatible with the clh